The programs that parse HTML now recognize a few more HTML5 elements (article, section, etc.). In addition, some improvements in the source code and in a regression test mean it should also compile out of the box on more systems. (Certain compiler options could previously cause a compile-time error. Reportedly, these options are enabled by default on Arch Linux.) See the ChangeLog for details. (News Archive)</description>       <link>http://www.w3.org/2014/01/SoftwareNews#x20141021a</link>       <dc:date>2014-10-21</dc:date>    </item>    <item rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/2014/01/SoftwareNews#x20140516a">       <title>csvtotab/tabtocsv 0.1</title>       <description>16 May 2014: First release of a pair of programs to convert between CSV (comma-separated values) and tab-separated values. They are intended to conform to the first draft (27 March 2014) of Model for Tabular Data and Metadata on the Web. See the source code (News Archive)</description>       <link>http://www.w3.org/2014/01/SoftwareNews#x20140516a</link>       <dc:date>2014-05-16</dc:date>    </item>    <item rdf:about="http://www.w3.org/2013/01/SoftwareNews#x20130812a">       <title>xmptool 0.9</title>       <description>12 August 2013: Version 0.9 of xmptool fixes a bug that made the program crash (reporting a failed assertion) if there were two properties in a row without a value.
